OVER 500 men and young boys gathered under one roof , united by the same thought: End abuse of women and children! Actors Patrick Shai and Sello Maake Ka Ncube were also in attendance at the Men’s Dialogue at the Birchwood Hotel, in Boksburg in Ekurhuleni. READ: ‘I’M KILLING MYSELF BECAUSE OF OUR DAUGHTER’ Gauteng Premier David Makhura called out men who use culture to justify brutal masculinity.  “Some men do things that are to their benefit and then say it is in their culture to do that,” he said. “We must confront these problems and address social norms, power relations and ensure that we build a society in which men and women live together in peace.” Makhura said some of the underlying sources of gender violence were issues of power relations and resources. “Some of the hidden causes of violence against women by men is when a woman works and earns money while the man earns less or has been retrenched or doesn’t work.” Makhura said that while empowering girls and women was necessary, boys should not be left out. “If we raise our boys so that they feel left out, there will be a problem later,” he said. “If they are left behind, they will end up in prison doing robberies and killing people because they are not making it in life. READ: BOSS FORCED ME TO SUCK HIS 4-5!  Talent Shezi (14) from Lenasia, south of Joburg, said what he learnt from the men’s dialogue is that men should not raise their hand on a woman. “When I get back home, I will tell my friends not to hit girls or touch them without asking for permission.”